The female antenna may be slightly serrate (
Fig. 11
) or filiform (
Fig. 1
). The male antennae have long rami, with antennomeres 3–8 or 4–8 bipectinate. For males, there are three basic patterns: ( 1 ) (
Fig. 26
) antennomere 3 unipectinate, antennomeres 4–6 bipectinate with inner ramus much shorter than outer ramus, and antennomeres 7 and 8 bipectinate with both rami subequal in length; ( 2 ) (
Fig. 25
) antennomeres 3–8 with long rami, antennomere 3 with inner ramus very short, antennomeres 4–8 with inner and outer rami long and subequal in length; and ( 3 ) (
Fig. 24
) similar to ( 2 ) but inner ramus of antennomere 3 long. Most males described in my 1990 revision were type ( 1 ); only one species,
L. longicus
, was type ( 2 ), and none that I saw at that time were type ( 3 ).

The male genitalia are useful, but all are very similar (
Figs. 27–34
). The shape of the parameres and penis valve give the best characters.

